generalfeedback.text:
integrations over the cube are of the form \(\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{@aa@} 
\int_{y=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{z=0}^{@aa@}  \mathrm{d}V.\)
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>The 
The mass \(M\) is given by
\begin{align*}
M &= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{y=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{z=0}^{@aa@} \rho \;\mathrm{d}z \,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x\\ 
&=\int_{x=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{y=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{z=0}^{@aa@}  k x \;\mathrm{d}z \,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\
&= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{y=0}^{@aa@}  {@I11@}  \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x = \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} 
  {@I12@}   \;\mathrm{d}x= \bigg[  {@fbI13@}  \bigg]_0^{@aa@}  =
{@ta1@}
  \end{align*}
</li>

<li>The \(x\)-coordinate of the centre of mass will be given by
\(\dfrac{\displaystyle\int \rho x \;\mathrm{d}V}{M}\) where the numerator is given by
\begin{align*}
\int\rho xdV &= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \int_{z=0}^{@aa@} \rho x \;\mathrm{d}z \,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x =
\int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \int_{z=0}^{@aa@}  k x^2 \;\mathrm{d}z \,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\
&= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} {@I2x1@}  \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x = \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}
  {@I2x2@}  \;\mathrm{d}x = \left[ {@fbI2x3@} \right]_0^{@aa@} =
{@I2x3@}
  \end{align*}
So \(\overline{x} ={@I2x3@}\div{@ta1@} = {@ta2x@}\). 
The \(y\)-coordinate of the centre of mass is given by \(\dfrac{\displaystyle\int
\rho y \;\mathrm{d}V}{M}\) where the numerator is given by
\begin{align*}
\int\rho y\mathrm{d}V &= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \int_{z=0}^{@aa@} \rho y \;\mathrm{d}z \,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x =
\int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \int_{z=0}^{@aa@} kyx \;\mathrm{d}z \,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\
&= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} {@I2y1@} \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x = \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}
  {@I2y2@}  \;\mathrm{d}x = \bigg[ {@fbI2y3@} \bigg]_0^{@aa@} =
{@I2y3@}
  \end{align*}
So \(\overline{y} = {@I2y3@}\div{@ta1@} = 1\). <br>
By symmetry (the density depends only on \(x\)), \(\overline{z} =
\overline{y} = {@ta2y@}\). The coordinates of the centre of mass are
(\({@ta2x@},{@ta2y@},{@ta2z@}\)).
</li>


<li>Finally find the moments of inertia about the \(x\)-, \(y\)- and \(z\)-axes:<br>
The moment of inertia about the \(x\)-axis is given by \(I_x = \int_V
\rho \left(y^2 + z^2 \right) \;\mathrm{d}V\). 
In this case,
\begin{align*}
I_x &= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \int_{z=0}^{@aa@} k x (y^2 + z^2) \;\mathrm{d}z
\,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\
&= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \left[ {@fbI3x1@} \right]_{z=0}^{@aa@} \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x = \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} {@I3x1@}  \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\
&=  \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \left[ {@fbI3x2@} \right]_{y=0}^{@aa@}\;\mathrm{d}x = \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}  {@I3x2@} \;\mathrm{d}x \\
&= \left[{@fbI3x3@} \right]_0^2 = {@I3x3@} ={@ta3x@}
\end{align*} where the last step involves substituting that the
mass \(M = 8k\).
Similarly, the moment of inertia about the \(y\)-axis is given by \(I_y
= \int_V \rho \left(x^2 + z^2 \right) \;\mathrm{d}V\) i.e. <br>
\begin{align*}
I_y &= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@} \int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \int_{z=0}^{@aa@} k x (x^2 + z^2) \;\mathrm{d}z
\,\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\
& =  \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}  \int_{y=0}^{@aa@}  \left[ {@fbI3y1@} \right]_{z=0}^{@aa@}  \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x \\ 
&= \int_{x=0}^{@aa@}
\int_{y=0}^{@aa@} \left( {@I3y1@} \right) \;\mathrm{d}y \,\mathrm{d}x =
\int_{x=0}^{@aa@}  \left( {@I3y2@} \right)  \;\mathrm{d}x \\
&=  \left[ {@fbI3y3@} \right]_{x=0}^{@aa@}  = {@I3y3@} =  {@ta3y@}
\end{align*}
By symmetry, \(I_z = I_y = {@ta3y@}\).
</li>
</ol>

